You took another "kapia".

448
01:21:25,000 --> 01:21:27,000
Slow down!

449
01:21:28,000 --> 01:21:32,000
I can't. 
Stop! Slower!

450
01:21:33,000 --> 01:21:36,000
We don't have brakes!
Stop, we'll kill ourselves!

451
01:21:37,000 --> 01:21:39,000
I can't, jump!

452
01:21:51,000 --> 01:21:53,000
Grandpa!

453
01:21:57,000 --> 01:21:59,000
Grandpa, where are you?

454
01:22:01,000 --> 01:22:05,000
Why are you shouting so much!?
Where am I? I'm here!

455
01:22:05,003 --> 01:22:12,000
Switzerland - 3 000 000. Austria - 2, France - 3.

456
01:22:13,000 --> 01:22:16,000
Damned rates just for crossing the border!

457
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:20,000
How much is it for Germany?
2 000 000

458
01:22:21,000 --> 01:22:27,000
Why Germany, Vasko? I'm for the USA. Where the high houses, the skyscrapers are. 

459
01:22:32,000 --> 01:22:36,000
I have a brother there in Chicago. He has a house at the Lake Michigan.

460
01:22:36,003 --> 01:22:41,000
People respect him much there. They value him. I expect his invitation any moment now.

461
01:22:41,003 --> 01:22:45,000
And then ... :D

462
01:22:45,003 --> 01:22:48,000
Come on, it's your turn. 
You hurry too much for my victory, wait a minute.

463
01:22:48,003 --> 01:22:53,000
It's true that a donkey and backgammon player understand only thrashing, but still ...

464
01:22:53,003 --> 01:22:57,000
Come on, bang on the head ... that's enough for you. 

465
01:22:57,003 --> 01:23:00,000
You're a great master, Vasko.

466
01:23:01,000 --> 01:23:07,000
2 000 000 is too much, damned. Too much.
Money is not a problem for you. 

467
01:23:08,000 --> 01:23:11,000
How come? This is 2 000 000, where would I find it?

468
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:16,000
Listen, there is something like bar here.

469
01:23:16,003 --> 01:23:19,000
Just opposite the train station. 

470
01:23:19,003 --> 01:23:23,000
They play all kinds of games there. Even backgammon but ... for money.

471
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:30,000
I don't play for money.
Stay here then. 

472
01:23:43,000 --> 01:23:46,000
It has a garage too.

473
01:24:13,000 --> 01:24:18,000
Avanti, avanti ... 
What "avanti", fuck you! I won't eat this shit!

474
01:25:15,000 --> 01:25:21,000
Somebody get up and say clearly what's going on here.

475
01:25:33,000 --> 01:25:37,000
Mr. Commandant!
What do you exactly want?

476
01:25:38,000 --> 01:25:41,000
Mr. Sfortza, I will explain.

477
01:25:41,003 --> 01:25:45,000
We are refugees from a dictatorship.

478
01:25:45,003 --> 01:25:52,000
We are not criminals. We have human rights! You keep us here for years.

479
01:25:52,003 --> 01:25:55,000
You turn us into prisoners.

480
01:25:55,003 --> 01:26:00,000
We don't want our children to grow here. People forgot their profession!

481
01:26:00,003 --> 01:26:04,000
Stop!
We won't take this any more!

482
01:26:04,003 --> 01:26:08,000
We all know that you get 10 $ a day per each one of us.

483
01:26:08,003 --> 01:26:13,000
For us! But you keep them for yourself. That's why we stay here for years.

484
01:26:13,003 --> 01:26:18,000
I've been here for 2 years, too.
Me - 2 years.
Give us back our documents.

485
01:26:18,003 --> 01:26:24,000
Strike! Strike!

486
01:26:28,000 --> 01:26:36,000
Quiet!
We want faster procedures, better food and language courses.

487
01:26:37,000 --> 01:26:41,000
Today we go on a hunger strike.

488
01:26:41,003 --> 01:26:45,000
That's what we've decided.
Who's on the strike? 

489
01:26:45,003 --> 01:26:49,000
All of us. We are all on a strike. 

490
01:26:49,003 --> 01:26:52,000
Whoever is on strike to raise their hands.

491
01:27:14,000 --> 01:27:18,000
Very good!
Nobody should have the illusion that

492
01:27:18,003 --> 01:27:23,000
a democratic country would tolerate anarchy and chaos.

493
01:27:24,000 --> 01:27:30,000
I have every right to bringing you back there, where you came from. 

494
01:27:32,000 --> 01:27:37,000
We don't need thrashers and vagabonds.

495
01:27:38,000 --> 01:27:43,000
Leave the canteen immediately!

496
01:28:05,000 --> 01:28:11,000
Wretches! You'll rot here!

497
01:28:57,000 --> 01:29:03,000
... What?
We'll earn some money.

498
01:29:03,003 --> 01:29:08,000
Count me out. This is illeagal.
Ok, you stay here.

499
01:29:13,000 --> 01:29:16,000
How much's the game?
20

500
01:29:22,000 --> 01:29:24,000
Come on, 20.

501
01:29:40,000 --> 01:29:43,000
100, 100 ... 100 ... 

502
01:30:20,000 --> 01:30:23,000
Let me see. Does it hurt?

503
01:30:23,003 --> 01:30:29,000
You're okay! Bastards! Come on!

504
01:30:29,003 --> 01:30:35,000
They've beaten you a little but ... we won some money.

505
01:30:35,003 --> 01:30:38,000
You are not mad, are you? We're going to the sea.

506
01:30:38,003 --> 01:30:44,000
You are crazy! Crazy! We almost died, they've beaten me,

507
01:30:44,003 --> 01:30:48,000
they've robbed me! The only thing left is to arrest me. 

508
01:30:48,003 --> 01:30:56,000
I'm not going further! Give my regards to Bulgaria!
But, Sashe, I'm sorry! Where are you going, Sashe?

509
01:30:57,000 --> 01:31:03,000
Sashe, get off! Get off!!!
Go, go, come on!

510
01:32:20,000 --> 01:32:23,000
You owe me 8 X the first bet.

511
01:32:31,000 --> 01:32:36,000
One more game?
Enough for today.

512
01:32:38,000 --> 01:32:41,000
Somebody else?

513
01:32:50,000 --> 01:32:53,000
How much do you bet?

514
01:32:58,000 --> 01:33:04,000
100 000
This is nothing. 

515
01:33:21,000 --> 01:33:24,000
Good, come on!

516
01:33:31,000 --> 01:33:39,000
We'll meet again, there's no way that we don't meet.
The world is small, you'll visit me in Chicago. Yane, cheer up!

517
01:33:39,003 --> 01:33:45,000
Sashe, listen to your parents but ... not too much.
Thank you so much.

518
01:33:46,000 --> 01:33:48,000
God be with you!

519
01:35:48,000 --> 01:35:52,000
We'll spend the night here.
Ok.

520
01:38:30,000 --> 01:38:37,000
Back, back! Go back to the girl! Introduce yourself, ask her where is she from. Should I teach you?

521
01:38:39,000 --> 01:38:45,000
That was just a dance.
Dance? Yap-yap I saw how she looked at you. Go back immediately!

522
01:38:45,003 --> 01:38:52,000
But ... I ... 
Don't mumble ... look at you, young, healthy, goodlooking and what is he doing?

523
01:38:53,000 --> 01:38:57,000
Go back immediately or I'll force you!

524
01:39:34,000 --> 01:39:37,000
But I live in Germany.

525
01:39:40,000 --> 01:39:45,000
We're going to the beach, are you coming?
Yes. 

526
01:41:19,000 --> 01:41:25,000
I don't remember anything before the accident.
I can write and read. 

527
01:41:25,003 --> 01:41:30,000
I know how to use the telephone but I don't know who are the people from my telephone directory.

528
01:41:32,000 --> 01:41:37,000
Now I am gathering my memories again ...

529
01:41:38,000 --> 01:41:43,000
What do you do?
I study ballet. 

530
01:41:45,000 --> 01:41:48,000
and I work in a salsa-club.

531
01:41:49,000 --> 01:41:55,000
When I saw you yesterday there was something sad in you but beautiful.

532
01:41:58,000 --> 01:42:02,000
I wanted you to hug me.

533
01:42:05,000 --> 01:42:10,000
Now where are you going?
Bulgaria. I was born there.

534
01:42:11,000 --> 01:42:16,000
We travel with my grandfather and a tandem.
What?

535
01:42:17,000 --> 01:42:21,000
Yes, you both look great.

536
01:42:25,000 --> 01:42:30,000
As for me, I'm going back to Germany.

537
01:42:31,000 --> 01:42:36,000
The fact that I don't remember my past has its good sides.

538
01:42:37,000 --> 01:42:42,000
It's as though you are the first girl I've been with.

539
01:42:45,000 --> 01:42:50,000
Probably I am ... 

540
01:42:51,000 --> 01:42:55,000
The first ... and the only one.

541
01:43:00,000 --> 01:43:04,000
So what's her name?
Maria.

542
01:43:04,000 --> 01:43:07,000
Did you fall in love?
Yes.

543
01:43:07,003 --> 01:43:15,000
Bravo, you didn't discredit me. You took the "Heavenly kapia" - the best one.

544
01:43:16,003 --> 01:43:20,000
There are only two left.

545
01:44:20,000 --> 01:44:24,000
Hey, stop there! 

546
01:44:28,000 --> 01:44:35,000
I've been here years ago with my mother and father. I want to look around.

547
01:44:37,000 --> 01:44:44,000
What's your name?
Alexander Georgiev. My father - Vasil, my mother - Yana.

548
01:44:45,000 --> 01:44:52,000
Sasho, is this you? I am Ivo (the:) Chicago.

549
01:44:53,000 --> 01:44:56,000
Don't you recognize me?

550
01:44:57,000 --> 01:45:03,000
See ... I got you again. Two for me.

551
01:45:09,000 --> 01:45:14,000
How are your mother and father, Sashe?
They passed away.

552
01:45:15,000 --> 01:45:17,000
Come on!?

553
01:45:19,000 --> 01:45:24,000
Stoyan too, do you remeber uncle Stoyan? The one who knew many languages.

554
01:45:24,003 --> 01:45:30,000
Not long after your departure he got very ill and in about half an year he passed away.

555
01:45:30,003 --> 01:45:35,000
May he rest in peace. And your mother and father too.

556
01:45:37,000 --> 01:45:40,000
What about you?
What about me?

557
01:45:40,003 --> 01:45:45,000
What happened with America?
I never got the invitation from my brother.

558
01:45:47,000 --> 01:45:55,000
I tried to call many times but ... 
Probably he didn't need me. He might have died, who knows.

559
01:45:55,003 --> 01:46:00,000
How come dead?
You probably think that people in America never die?

560
01:46:00,003 --> 01:46:04,000
They die like flies. Don't you watch TV? 

561
01:46:04,003 --> 01:46:10,000
You are sitting somewhere, eating your burger, drinking your drink and suddenly

562
01:46:10,003 --> 01:46:15,000
some guy, who's at odds with the world, comes in with a gun that big and he starts shooting in order ... 

563
01:46:17,000 --> 01:46:23,000
Eh, America is hopeless case! I stayed here, Sashe, here. In the lager.

564
01:46:24,000 --> 03:32:30,000
A guard.

565
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:52,000
Good morning!

566
01:48:54,000 --> 01:48:57,000
Good morning, Sashe!
Where's grandpa?

567
01:48:57,003 --> 01:49:01,000
Early in the morning he left for Bulgaria with the train. He left the board for you.

568
01:50:23,000 --> 01:50:40,000
"For new Bulgaria!"

569
01:51:23,000 --> 01:51:32,000
Sashko! Sashe, granny's sugar cube!

570
01:53:18,000 --> 01:53:27,000
Sashko, my grandson!
Come on, Sashe! Welcome! What a man have you become!

571
01:53:27,003 --> 01:53:40,000
He became bigger than us! (song)

572
01:53:42,000 --> 01:53:47,000
We'll see him now if he took after his grandpa.
Eeeeh, of course!
Be careful not to cry afterwards.

573
01:53:47,003 --> 01:53:51,000
Oh, no, no ... 
If you're going to withdraw, now is the time to do it.
no, no, no, I'm not ... 

574
01:53:51,003 --> 01:53:56,000
You're not?
No?
No. Come on!!!

575
01:53:58,000 --> 01:54:04,000
Now, the winner would become the one who first get two games in a row. 

576
01:54:06,000 --> 01:54:11,000
If it gets dark and we still haven't got a winner, you'll throw the dice.

577
01:54:11,003 --> 01:54:17,000
The one who throws the bigger number he'll become the King of Backgammon. Is it clear? 

578
01:54:22,000 --> 01:54:26,000
Now, let's see, who'll be the first.

579
01:55:40,000 --> 01:55:42,000
Come on, this is for the  kibitzers.

580
01:56:13,000 --> 01:56:18,000
All the day none of the players could win two games more than the other.

581
01:56:22,000 --> 01:56:28,000
It got dark. Then it became clear that dice must decide who's the King of Backgammon.

582
01:56:28,003 --> 01:56:34,000
Just one throw. The one who throws the bigger nuber wins.

583
01:59:54,000 --> 02:00:01,000
I threw six and seven. Nowhere and never such a thing had happened.

584
02:00:03,000 --> 02:00:07,000
I took the "Royal kapia" - the last one.

585
02:00:10,000 --> 02:00:14,000
I was cured. 

586
02:00:47,000 --> 02:00:55,000
I could start from the begining. To dream, to play, to lose and to win.

587
02:00:56,000 --> 02:01:02,000
To be, now and forever. Because as my grandpa said: 

588
02:01:03,000 --> 02:01:07,000
"The world is big and salvation lurks around the corner"
